  "prompt": "Why does adenine combine with thymine only and not cytosine?",
  "response": "Adenine (A) and Thymine (T) pair specifically due to their chemical structures and the resulting hydrogen bonds they can form. Here's a breakdown of why A-T pairing is favored over A-C:\n\n*   **Hydrogen Bonding:** The key to DNA base pairing lies in the ability to form stable hydrogen bonds between the bases.\n    *   Adenine has two hydrogen bond donors and one hydrogen bond acceptor.\n    *   Thymine has two hydrogen bond acceptors and one hydrogen bond donor.\n\n    When Adenine and Thymine come together, they can form **two stable hydrogen bonds** between them. These two hydrogen bonds provide the optimal stability for the base pair.\n\n*   **Cytosine's hydrogen bonding:** Cytosine has one hydrogen bond donor and two hydrogen bond acceptors.\n\n    *   Adenine and Cytosine can technically form hydrogen bonds, but they form **fewer and less stable bonds**. The geometry of the molecules doesn't align to allow for the ideal formation of hydrogen bonds. If they force themselves together, it disrupts the normal geometry of the DNA double helix.\n\n*   **Steric Compatibility:** The shapes and sizes of adenine and thymine are complementary. This means they fit together snugly within the double helix structure without causing distortion.\n\n    *   The combination of A and C would cause significant distortion in the structure of the DNA because their size differences would cause a bulge.\n\nIn summary, A-T pairing is favored because it allows for the formation of two stable hydrogen bonds and fits perfectly within the DNA double helix structure without causing distortion. The chemical structure of cytosine cannot form a stable two-hydrogen bond pairing with adenine, and it would create structural distortions in the DNA.",
